'''Yassine Bounou'''{{Refn|group=note|({{langx|ar|ياسين بونو}}, {{langx|ber|ⵢⴰⵙⵉⵏ ⴱⵓⵏⵓ}})<ref>{{Cite web |title=ⵎⵓⵏⴹⵢⴰⵍ ⵇⵇⴰⵟⴰⵕ 2022 .. ⴰⵎⵙⵙⴰⵏⵓⵏ ⴰⵏⴰⵎⵓⵔ ⵡⴰⵍⵉⴷ ⵔⵔⴳⵔⴰⴳⵉ ⵉⴼⵙⵔ ⴰⵙⵙⴰⵖⵏ ⵏ ⵉⵣⵎⴰⵡⵏ ⵏ ⵡⴰⵟⵍⴰⵚ |url=https://www.mapnews.ma/am/actualites/%E2%B5%9C%E2%B5%93%E2%B5%8F%E2%B5%8F%E2%B5%93%E2%B5%8F%E2%B5%9C/%E2%B5%8E%E2%B5%93%E2%B5%8F%E2%B4%B9%E2%B5%A2%E2%B4%B0%E2%B5%8D-%E2%B5%87%E2%B5%87%E2%B4%B0%E2%B5%9F%E2%B4%B0%E2%B5%95-2022-%E2%B4%B0%E2%B5%8E%E2%B5%99%E2%B5%99%E2%B4%B0%E2%B5%8F%E2%B5%93%E2%B5%8F-%E2%B4%B0%E2%B5%8F%E2%B4%B0%E2%B5%8E%E2%B5%93%E2%B5%94-%E2%B5%A1%E2%B4%B0%E2%B5%8D%E2%B5%89%E2%B4%B7-%E2%B5%94%E2%B5%94%E2%B4%B3%E2%B5%94%E2%B4%B0%E2%B4%B3%E2%B5%89-%E2%B5%89%E2%B4%BC%E2%B5%99%E2%B5%94-%E2%B4%B0%E2%B5%99%E2%B5%99%E2%B4%B0%E2%B5%96%E2%B5%8F-%E2%B5%8F-%E2%B5%89%E2%B5%A3%E2%B5%8E%E2%B4%B0%E2%B5%A1%E2%B5%8F-%E2%B5%8F-%E2%B5%A1%E2%B4%B0%E2%B5%9F%E2%B5%8D%E2%B4%B0%E2%B5%9A |access-date=3 December 2022 |website=[[Maghreb Arabe Presse]]}}</ref>}} (born 5 April 1991), also known mononymously as''' Bono''', is a Moroccan professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] for [[Saudi Professional League|Saudi Pro League]] club [[Al Hilal SFC|Al Hilal]] and the [[Morocco national football team|Morocco national team]].

Bono began his youth career in Morocco, playing for [[Wydad AC]]. He spent most of his senior career in Spain, making over 150 [[La Liga]] appearances, and over 50 in the [[Segunda División]]. During the [[2021–22 La Liga|2021–22 season]], he won the [[Zamora Trophy]] for the first time in the history of [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]].  Bono was ranked thirteenth for the 2023 [[Ballon d'Or]] while third and for the 2023 [[Yashin Trophy]] respectively. He also ranked third place for [[The Best FIFA Goalkeeper]] in 2022 and 2023, and second place by the [[IFFHS World's Best Goalkeeper]] in 2022, at the international level, he achieved fourth place with his national team in the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]].

Born in Canada to Moroccan parents, Bono returned to Morocco at the age of three with his family. He has been a full international for Morocco since 2013. Having previously played for the [[Morocco national under-23 football team|under-23 team]] at the [[Football at the 2012 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament|2012 Olympics]], he has represented his nation at two [[FIFA World Cup]] and five [[Africa Cup of Nations]] tournaments.

==Club career==
Bounou was born in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]]. His father, originally from the village of Bouana in the province of [[Taounate]], is an engineer and former professor at the [[Hassania School of Public Works]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=ساكنة تمضيت تخرج للاحتفال بمرور المنتخب لربع نهائي مونديال قطر |url=https://alyaoum24.com/1750637.html |access-date=2024-11-13 |website=Alyaoum24 |language=ar}}</ref><ref name="JA">{{Cite web |last=Billebault |first=Alexis |title=Maroc – Qatar 2022 : Bounou, la force tranquille |url=https://www.jeuneafrique.com/1398915/societe/maroc-qatar-2022-bounou-la-force-tranquille/ |access-date=2024-11-13 |website=[[Jeune Afrique]] |language=fr-FR}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Imray |first1=Gerald |title=Morocco 2018 FIFA World Cup preview: Everything you need to know |url=https://www.denverpost.com/2018/06/13/morocco-2018-fifa-world-cup-preview/ |access-date=22 October 2021 |work=[[The Denver Post]] |date=13 June 2018}}</ref> Bounou and his parents returned to Morocco when he was three years old, settling in [[Casablanca]].<ref name="JA" /> He began playing football as a child and joined [[Wydad AC]] at the age of 8 in 1999. He liked to play using his feet, but due to his height it was later suggested he become a goalkeeper, a challenge he accepted. His goalkeeper idol is [[Edwin van der Sar]]. His parents initially had mixed feelings regarding their son spending so much time playing football, but they later became more supportive as his talent became more evident. At 17 years old, his goalkeeping skills were spotted by a scout from [[OGC Nice]], and he signed with the club; however due to bureaucratic problems he ended up not playing for Nice, and he returned to Wydad AC. In 2011, he made his senior debut in the club, after having been promoted to the first-team a year earlier.<ref>{{cite web |title=Yassine Bounou: El meta rebelde |date=18 July 2013 |url=https://www.mundodeportivo.com/20130718/atletico-madrid/yassine-bounou-portero-perfil_54377629633.html |publisher=[[Mundo Deportivo]] |access-date=7 December 2022}}</ref>

=== Wydad AC ===
[[File:Yassine Bounou.jpg|left|thumb|338x338px|Bounou with [[Wydad AC]] in 2012]]
Bono moved to the first team in 2010 at the age of nineteen as the second choice keeper, behind [[Nadir Lamyaghri]]. He started his first match with the Wydad AC first team in front of 80,000 supporters on the occasion of the final of the [[2011 CAF Champions League|CAF Champions League]] against Espérance de Tunis.

On 21 November 2011, Bono played his first Botola Pro match against [[Difaâ El Jadida]]. He took part in ten league matches, and then he moved to [[Atlético Madrid]].

=== Atlético Madrid ===
On 14 June 2012, Bono moved to [[La Liga]] club [[Atlético Madrid]], where he was initially named to the second team [[Atlético Madrid B|the reserves]] in [[Segunda División B]],<ref>[http://www.goal.com/es/news/21/fichajes/2012/06/14/3172897/el-atl%C3%A9tico-de-madrid-ficha-al-internacional-marroqu%C3%AD El Atlético de Madrid ficha al internacional marroquí Yassine Bounou para su filial (Atlético Madrid signs Moroccan international Yassine Bounou to their reserve squad)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191018081356/https://www.goal.com/es/news/21/fichajes/2012/06/14/3172897/el-atl%C3%A9tico-de-madrid-ficha-al-internacional-marroqu%C3%AD |date=18 October 2019 }}; Goal.com, 14 June 2012 {{in lang|es}}</ref> and as a third goalkeeper with the first team. He signed a new four-year deal with the club on 31 May 2013.<ref>[http://www.mundodeportivo.com/20130531/atletico-madrid/portero-bono-renovacion-2017_54375005140.html Bono renueva por el cuadro colchonero hasta 2017 (Bono renews for the ''colchoneros'' until 2017)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401130356/https://www.mundodeportivo.com/20130531/atletico-madrid/portero-bono-renovacion-2017_54375005140.html |date=1 April 2019 }}; [[Mundo Deportivo (newspaper)|Mundo Deportivo]], 31 May 2013 {{in lang|es}}</ref> In the summer of 2014, after profiting from [[Thibaut Courtois]] and [[Daniel Aranzubia]]'s departures, he was definitively promoted to the main squad. He made his first-team debut on 24 July 2014, in a 1–0 pre-season [[Exhibition match|friendly]] win against [[CD Numancia|Numancia]].<ref>[http://en.clubatleticodemadrid.com/noticias/siqueira-im-happy-to-debut-with-atletico Siqueira: "I'm happy to have made my debut with Atlético"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306224722/http://en.clubatleticodemadrid.com/noticias/siqueira-im-happy-to-debut-with-atletico |date=6 March 2016 }}; Atlético Madrid, 24 July 2014</ref>

=== Zaragoza ===
On 1 September 2014, Bono was loaned to the [[Segunda División]]'s [[Real Zaragoza]], in a [[2014–15 Segunda División|season]]-long deal.<ref>[https://www.clubatleticodemadrid.com/noticias/acuerdo-con-el-real-zaragoza-para-la-cesion-de-bounou Acuerdo con el Real Zaragoza para la cesión de Bounou (Agreement with Real Zaragoza for the loan of Bounou)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306204944/http://clubatleticodemadrid.com/noticias/acuerdo-con-el-real-zaragoza-para-la-cesion-de-bounou |date=6 March 2016 }}; Atlético Madrid, 1 September 2014 {{in lang|es}}</ref> Kept out by [[Óscar Whalley]] for the first half of the campaign, he made his debut the following 11 January in a 5–3 loss at [[UD Las Palmas]], and finished the season with 16 appearances. In the [[2015 Segunda División play-offs|play-offs]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ferrer|first1=Pedro Luis|title=El Girona sentencia en la noche negra de Óscar Whalley|trans-title=Girona sentence Óscar Whalley's black night|url=https://futbol.as.com/futbol/2015/06/11/segunda/1434043739_199416.html|access-date=21 March 2016|publisher=Diario AS|date=11 June 2015|language=es}}</ref> after Whalley's performance led to a 0–3 home loss to [[Girona FC]] in the first leg, Bounou replaced him in the second for a 4–1 win and advancement on away goals;<ref>{{cite news|last1=Moya|first1=Ángel|title=Zaragoza obra el milagro|trans-title=Zaragoza work a miracle|url=https://www.marca.com/eventos/marcador/futbol/2014_15/promocion_ascenso/semifinal/vuelta/ger_zar/|access-date=21 March 2016|publisher=Marca|date=14 June 2015|language=es}}</ref> Zaragoza lost the final by the same rule to [[UD Las Palmas]]. On 23 July 2015, he returned to the [[Aragon]]ese side, again in a one-year loan deal.<ref>[http://www.realzaragoza.com/noticias/51857 El guardameta Bounou jugará una temporada más en el Real Zaragoza (Goalkeeper Bounou will play a further season at Real Zaragoza)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150723215608/http://www.realzaragoza.com/noticias/51857 |date=23 July 2015 }}; Real Zaragoza, 23 July 2015 {{in lang|es}}</ref>

=== Girona ===
On 12 July 2016, Bounou signed a permanent two-year contract with fellow league team Girona.<ref>[http://www.gironafc.cat/noticia/el-girona-fc-completa-la-porteria-amb-el-fitxatge-de-bono El Girona FC completa la porteria amb el fitxatge de Bono (Girona FC complete the goal with the signing of Bono)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160715125330/http://www.gironafc.cat/noticia/el-girona-fc-completa-la-porteria-amb-el-fitxatge-de-bono |date=15 July 2016 }}; Girona FC, 12 July 2016 {{in lang|es}}</ref> He played exactly half of games in his first season – sharing with [[René Román]] – as they were [[2016–17 Segunda División|promoted in second place]]. In January 2019, now first choice at the top-flight club, he extended his contract until June 2021.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Solà |first1=Nil |title=Oficial: Bono renueva con el Girona hasta 2021|trans-title=Official: Bono renews with Girona until 2021|url=https://www.mundodeportivo.com/futbol/girona-fc/20190111/454073977080/girona-bono-renovacion.html |access-date=22 October 2021 |work=Mundo Deportivo |date=11 January 2019 |language=Spanish}}</ref>

=== Sevilla ===
[[File:Yassine bounou Interview 2023.jpg|thumb|334x334px|Bounou with [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] in 2023]]
On 2 September 2019, after [[2018–19 La Liga|suffering relegation]] with the [[Girona FC|Catalans]], Bounou joined [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] in the top tier, on loan for one year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sevillafc.es/en/actual/news/bono-arrives-on-loan|title=Yassine Bounou arrives on loan from Girona FC|publisher=Sevilla FC|date=2 September 2019|access-date=3 September 2019}}</ref> Second-choice to [[Tomáš Vaclík]] in the league season, he played regularly in the domestic cup and as the side won the [[2019–20 UEFA Europa League]], earning plaudits for his performance against [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] in the quarter-finals as he saved a penalty from [[Raúl Jiménez]] to earn a 1–0 win,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sevillafc.es/en/actual/news/bono-wolves-uel-1920 |title=Bono on the win against Wolves |website=sevillafc.es |date=11 August 2020 }}</ref> also in the 2–1 semi-final win over [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=McNulty |first1=Phil |title=Sevilla 2–1 Manchester United |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/53793942 |access-date=21 August 2020 |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=16 August 2020}}</ref> and eventually his decisive save of [[Romelu Lukaku]]'s one-on-one strike, to win the [[2020 UEFA Europa League Final|final]] 3–2 against [[Inter Milan]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/53815528 |title=Seville 3–2 Inter Milan |website=BBC Sport |date=21 August 2020 }}</ref>

On 4 September 2020, Bono signed a permanent four-year contract with the Andalusians.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sevillafc.es/actualidad/noticias/sevilla-fc-cierrra-traspaso-bono|title=El Sevilla FC cierra el traspaso de Yassine Bounou|trans-title=Sevilla FC complete the transfer of Yassine Bounou|publisher=Sevilla FC|language=es|date=4 September 2020|access-date=4 September 2020}}</ref> The following 21 March, in the last minute of a match against [[Real Valladolid]], he scored his first [[List of goalscoring goalkeepers|goal as a professional goalkeeper]] to secure a 1–1 draw.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Oludare |first1=Shina |title=Bounou's last-gasp goal denies Orellana and Real Valladolid |url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/bounous-last-gasp-goal-denies-orellana-and-real-valladolid/hav9bgjaqquy1pngvu93vwrqh |website=Goal |access-date=21 March 2021 |date=21 March 2021}}</ref> In the calendar year 2021, Bono kept 32 clean sheets in 59 games for club and country, the most for any goalkeeper in [[Big Five (association football)|Europe's top five leagues]] (second place was [[Ederson (footballer, born 1993)|Ederson]] of [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] and [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]], with 30 in 59).<ref>{{cite news |title=Bono finishes 2021 with the most clean sheets in Europe's top five leagues |url=https://sevillafc.es/en/actual/news/bono-clean-sheets-2021 |access-date=27 December 2022 |publisher=Sevilla FC |date=1 January 2022 |archive-date=26 December 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221226202447/https://sevillafc.es/en/actual/news/bono-clean-sheets-2021 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

On 27 February 2022, Bounou [[Assist (association football)|assisted]] a goal by international teammate [[Munir El Haddadi]] in a 2–1 win over [[Real Betis]] in the [[Seville derby]], his fourth goal contribution for Sevilla (three assists and a goal).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Espina |first1=José A. |title=La ley del Sevilla|trans-title=Sevilla's law |url=https://as.com/futbol/2022/02/27/primera/1645971885_233863.html |access-date=27 December 2022 |work=Diario AS |date=27 February 2022 |language=Spanish}}</ref> In April, his contract was extended by one year to 2025.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bono amplía su contrato con el Sevilla hasta 2025 |url=https://www.marca.com/futbol/sevilla/2022/04/19/625f0143e2704e156b8b45c8.html |access-date=27 December 2022 |work=Marca |date=10 April 2022 |language=Spanish}}</ref> After claiming the La Liga [[Ricardo Zamora Trophy]] for [[2021–22 La Liga|2021–22]]<ref name="Zamora22"/> (the first recipient playing for a club other than [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]], [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] or [[Atlético Madrid]] since [[Roberto Abbondanzieri]] of [[Getafe CF|Getafe]] in [[2005–06 La Liga|2006–07]]), Bounou was nominated for [[The Best FIFA Football Awards 2022|The Best FIFA Men's Goalkeeper]] at the end of 2022 along with [[Emiliano Martínez]] and [[Thibaut Courtois]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/fifaplus/en/articles/the-best-fifa-mens-goalkeeper-finalists-bounou-courtois-martinez |title=The Best FIFA Men's Goalkeeper finalists revealed|date=13 January 2023 |publisher=FIFA }}</ref> in which he eventually finished in second place.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/fifaplus/en/articles/tbffa-2022-the-best-fifa-mens-goalkeeper-martinez-bounou-courtois|title=World Cup hero Martinez wins Best FIFA Men's Goalkeeper honour|website=FIFA.com|publisher=Fédération Internationale de Football Association|date=27 February 2023|access-date=27 February 2023}}</ref>

On 31 May 2023, Bono was named Player of the Match in the [[2023 UEFA Europa League final|Europa League final]] against [[A.S. Roma|Roma]], where he managed to save two penalty kicks in a 4–1 victory for Sevilla in the penalty shootout after a 1–1 draw, which secured their seventh title in the competition.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/0281-1825b4ea6706-f267d32f6051-1000/ |title=Yassine Bounou named official UEFA Europa League final Hankook Player of the Match |website=[[UEFA]] |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=31 May 2023 |access-date=31 May 2023}}</ref> He was among the final three nominees for the 2023 [[The Best FIFA Football Awards 2023|Best FIFA Men's Goalkeeper]] alongside Courtois again, and eventual winner Ederson.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/fifaplus/en/the-best-fifa-football-awards/articles/the-best-mens-goalkeeper-finalists-revealed-bonou-courtois-ederson |title=The Best FIFA Men's Goalkeeper finalists revealed |date=12 December 2023 |publisher=FIFA }}</ref>

=== Al-Hilal ===
On 17 August 2023, Bono joined [[Riyadh]]-based side [[Al Hilal SFC|Al-Hilal]] on a three-year contract.<ref>{{Cite web |title=بعقد يمتد حتّى 2026.. "بـونـو" إلى كبيــر آسيا |trans-title=With a contract extending until 2026... "Bono" to the Asian giants |url=https://alhilal.com/12780 |access-date=2023-08-18 |website=alhilal.com |language=ar}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-08-16 |title=Morocco's Yassine Bounou Reportedly Reaches Agreement with Al Hilal |url=https://en.hespress.com/69264-moroccos-yassine-bounou-reportedly-reaches-agreement-with-al-hilal.html |access-date=2023-08-29 |website=Hesprees English - Morocco News |language=en-US}}</ref> In 2023, Bounou was nominated for the [[2023 Ballon d'Or]]<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-09-06 |title=Ballon d'Or 2023: Nominees revealed for the Golden Ball with Lionel Messi, Erling Haaland and Kylian Mbappe all in contention |url=https://www.goal.com/en/lists/ballon-dor-2023-nominees-revealed-golden-ball/bltd30128bf3edd43ae |access-date=2023-09-06 |website=www.goal.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-09-06 |title=Messi, Haaland lead nominees for '23 Ballon d'Or |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/38337365/ballon-dor-award-2023-messi-haaland-lead-nominees |access-date=2023-09-06 |website=ESPN.com |language=en}}</ref> and [[The Best FIFA Football Awards 2023|The 2023 Best FIFA Football Awards]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Kasraoui |first=Safaa |date=14 September 2023 |title=Yassine Bounou Among Best FIFA Men's Goalkeeper Nominees |pages=1 |work=Morocco World News |url=https://www.moroccoworldnews.com/2023/09/357693/yassine-bounou-among-best-fifa-mens-goalkeeper-nominees}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-09-14 |title=Best FIFA Football Awards 2023 nominations - revealed |url=https://www.90min.com/posts/best-fifa-football-awards-2023-nominations-revealed |access-date=2023-09-14 |website=90min.com |language=en-GB}}</ref> On 30 October 2023, Bounou was ranked 13th place in the [[2023 Ballon d'Or]]<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-10-30 |title=Yassine Bono ranks 13th for 2023's Ballon d'Or |url=https://en.hespress.com/73685-yassine-bono-ranks-13th-for-2023s-ballon-dor.html |access-date=2023-10-31 |website=HESPRESS English - Morocco News |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-10-30 |title=Ballon d'Or 2023 official rankings: Lionel Messi beats Erling Haaland and Kylian Mbappe to claim eighth Golden Ball {{!}} Goal.com |url=https://www.goal.com/en/lists/ballon-dor-2023-official-rankings/blt67b37a84a3acec81 |access-date=2023-10-31 |website=www.goal.com |language=en}}</ref> and ranked 3rd in the 2023 Yashin Trophy.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Summerscales |first=Robert |date=2023-10-30 |title=Emiliano Martinez Wins Yashin Trophy Despite NOT Being Top Goalkeeper In Ballon d'Or Vote |url=https://www.si.com/fannation/soccer/futbol/news/emi-martinez-wins-yashin-trophy-but-not-top-goalkeeper-in-ballon-dor-vote |access-date=2023-10-31 |website=Futbol on FanNation |language=en}}</ref> On 1 November 2023, Bounou was nominated for the 2023 [[African Footballer of the Year]] and 2023 African Goalkeeper of the Year by [[Confederation of African Football|CAF]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-01-11 |title=CAF announces CAF Awards 2023 Nominees for Men's Categories |url=https://www.cafonline.com/news/caf-announces-caf-awards-2023-nominees-for-men-s-categories/ |access-date=2023-11-01 |website=CAF |language=en-GB}}</ref> On 11 December 2023, Bono won the best goalkeeper in Africa trophy at the [[Confederation of African Football|CAF]].<ref name="en.hespress.com">{{Cite web |date=2023-12-11 |title=Morocco's Yassine Bono crowned best goalkeeper in Africa |url=https://en.hespress.com/76249-moroccos-yassine-bono-crowned-best-goalkeeper-in-africa.html |access-date=2023-12-12 |website=HESPRESS English - Morocco News |language=en-US}}</ref>

During the [[2025 FIFA Club World Cup]], he saved a late penalty from [[Federico Valverde]] in the opening match, maintaining a 1–1 draw against [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Tan |first=Gabriel |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/45540476/yassine-bounou-penalty-heroics-thwart-spain-finest-again-al-hilal-make-statement-real-madrid-draw |title=Yassine Bounou's penalty heroics thwart Spain's finest again as Al Hilal make statement with Real Madrid draw |publisher=ESPN |date=18 June 2025 }}</ref> In the competition's round of 16, he produced 10 saves including a crucial one-on-one stop against [[Savinho]] in a 4–3 victory after extra time over [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]], matching the record set by [[Thibaut Courtois]] in the same edition.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://onefootball.com/de/news/club-world-cup-yassine-bounou-matches-a-prestigious-record-41314770 |title=Club World Cup: Yassine Bounou matches a prestigious record |publisher=OneFootball |date=1 July 2025 }}</ref>

==International career==
[[File:Bounou.jpg|200px|thumb|right|Bounou with [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]] in 2023]]
Bounou was eligible to represent Canada or Morocco,<ref>[http://www.tangerinter.com/%D8%A3%D8%AA%D9%84%D9%8A%D8%AA%D9%8A%D9%83%D9%88-%D9%85%D8%AF%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%AF-%D9%8A%D8%B9%D9%8A%D8%B1-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AD%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%B3-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%BA%D8%B1%D8%A8%D9%8A-%D9%8A%D8%A7/ أتليتيكو  مدريد يعير الحارس المغربي ياسين بونو لسرقسطة (Atlético Madrid loans Moroccan goalkeeper Bounou to Zaragoza)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140901221210/http://www.tangerinter.com/%D8%A3%D8%AA%D9%84%D9%8A%D8%AA%D9%8A%D9%83%D9%88-%D9%85%D8%AF%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%AF-%D9%8A%D8%B9%D9%8A%D8%B1-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AD%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%B3-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%BA%D8%B1%D8%A8%D9%8A-%D9%8A%D8%A7/ |date=1 September 2014 }}; Tanger Inter, 31 August 2014 {{in lang|ar}}</ref> but opted to represent the latter, appearing with the [[Morocco national under-20 football team|under-20]] team at the [[2012 Toulon Tournament]], playing in one match during the competition. He was also selected in the 18-man [[Morocco national under-23 football team|under-23]] squad for the [[2012 Summer Olympics]], but acted as a backup to [[Mohamed Amsif]] during the tournament, in which Morocco were eliminated at the [[Football at the 2012 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament – Group D|group stage]].

In an interview, Bounou said that he had been contacted by the manager of the [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada national team]], [[Benito Floro]], but that this ultimately did not materialise. Moreover, he said to the interviewer that he grew up in Morocco, and deep down dreamed of representing the Moroccan national team.<ref>{{cite AV media |date=29 November 2022 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EPYYo-cJEUE |title=Yassine Bounou : "J'ai failli jouer pour le Canada"|trans-title=Yassine Bounou: "I almost played for Canada"|publisher=H24Info.ma |via=[[YouTube]] |access-date=20 December 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221210181256/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EPYYo-cJEUE |archive-date=10 December 2022 |url-status=live|language=French}}</ref>

On 14 August 2013, Bounou was called up to the [[Morocco national football team|main squad]] for a friendly match against [[Burkina Faso national football team|Burkina Faso]].<ref>[http://www.bladi.net/match-football-maroc-burkina-faso-aujourdhui.html Match Maroc – Burkina Faso Aujourd'hui (Match Morocco – Burkina Faso today)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191112103328/http://www.bladi.net/match-football-maroc-burkina-faso-aujourdhui.html |date=12 November 2019 }}; Bladi, 14 August 2013 {{in lang|fr}}</ref> He made his debut in the following day, playing the entire second half of an eventual 1–2 defeat in [[Tangier]].<ref>[http://www.lefaso.net/spip.php?article55443  Maroc – Burkina: Les Etalons triomphent à Tanger (Morocco – Burkina: The ''Etalons'' triumph in Tangier)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201031041135/http://www.lefaso.net/spip.php?article55443 |date=31 October 2020 }}; Le Faso, 15 August 2013 {{in lang|fr}}</ref>

In May 2018, Bounou was named in Morocco's 23-man squad for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] in Russia,<ref>{{cite web|title=Boufal left out of Morocco squad|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/amp/football/441603882018|publisher=BBC Sport}}{{Dead link|date=June 2023 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> where he served as reserve goalkeeper to [[Munir Mohamedi]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2390744/bounou-takes-long-road-to-morocco-stardom|title=Bounou takes long road to Morocco stardom|access-date=5 November 2023|date=12 December 2022|website=The Express Tribune}}</ref> At the [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations]] in Egypt he was first choice for [[Hervé Renard]]'s team, keeping clean sheets in 1–0 wins over [[Namibia national football team|Namibia]] and the [[Ivory Coast national football team|Ivory Coast]] to qualify for the last 16.<ref>{{cite news |title=Morocco 1–0 Namibia |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/48651171 |access-date=20 November 2019 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=23 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Morocco 1–0 Ivory Coast |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/48714570 |access-date=20 November 2019 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=28 June 2019}}</ref>

Bounou was also called up for the [[2021 Africa Cup of Nations]] in [[Cameroon]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Afcon 2021: Hakim Ziyech not recalled to Morocco squad for tournament in Cameroon |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/africa/59769523 |access-date=24 December 2021 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=23 December 2021}}</ref> At the tournament, he made headlines for his defense of [[Arabic]] and refusal to speak to the press in French or English; a jab at the [[African Nations Cup]] for not having hired a single Arabic translator.<ref>{{Cite news|title=جدل حول استخدام "لغة الضاد" في كأس الأمم الإفريقية|language=ar|work=BBC News عربي|url=https://www.bbc.com/arabic/trending-59995701|access-date=17 January 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=13 January 2022|title=بسبب غياب مترجم للعربية.. بونو يرفض التحدث بلغة أخرى في المؤتمر الصحفي|url=https://arabic.cnn.com/sport/article/2022/01/13/bono-refuses-speaking-other-arabic|access-date=17 January 2022|website=CNN Arabic|language=ar}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=الحارس ياسين بونو يحرج منظمي "الكان" ويرفض الإجابة بلغة أجنبية|url=http://www.casa24.ma/sport/38345.html|access-date=17 January 2022|website=كازا 24|language=ar}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=صبحي|first=هشام|date=13 January 2022|title=الكاف يُغضب ياسين بونو بعد منعه من استخدام اللغة العربية|url=https://www.alroeya.com/3-11/2261972-الكاف-يغضب-ياسين-بونو-بعد-منعه-من-استخدام-اللغة-العربية|access-date=17 January 2022|website=صحيفة الرؤية|language=ar}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title="تلك مشكلتكم".. فيديو لحارس المغرب بونو يجيب بالعربية ويرفض الترجمة {{!}} الحرة|url=https://www.alhurra.com/sport/2022/01/14/%D8%AA%D9%84%D9%83-%D9%85%D8%B4%D9%83%D9%84%D8%AA%D9%83%D9%85-%D9%81%D9%8A%D8%AF%D9%8A%D9%88-%D9%84%D8%AD%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%B3-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%BA%D8%B1%D8%A8-%D8%A8%D9%88%D9%86%D9%88-%D9%8A%D8%AC%D9%8A%D8%A8-%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%B1%D8%A8%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D9%88%D9%8A%D8%B1%D9%81%D8%B6-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%AC%D9%85%D8%A9|access-date=17 January 2022|website=www.alhurra.com|language=ar|archive-date=8 February 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220208012152/https://www.alhurra.com/sport/2022/01/14/%D8%AA%D9%84%D9%83-%D9%85%D8%B4%D9%83%D9%84%D8%AA%D9%83%D9%85-%D9%81%D9%8A%D8%AF%D9%8A%D9%88-%D9%84%D8%AD%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%B3-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%BA%D8%B1%D8%A8-%D8%A8%D9%88%D9%86%D9%88-%D9%8A%D8%AC%D9%8A%D8%A8-%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%B1%D8%A8%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D9%88%D9%8A%D8%B1%D9%81%D8%B6-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%AC%D9%85%D8%A9|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Hussien.Ghazi|title=ياسين بونو ينزعج في مؤتمر صحافي بسبب اللغة العربية|url=https://www.alaraby.co.uk/sport/%D9%8A%D8%A7%D8%B3%D9%8A%D9%86-%D8%A8%D9%88%D9%86%D9%88-%D9%8A%D9%86%D8%B2%D8%B9%D8%AC-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D9%85%D8%A4%D8%AA%D9%85%D8%B1-%D8%B5%D8%AD%D8%A7%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%A8%D8%B3%D8%A8%D8%A8-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%84%D8%BA%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%B1%D8%A8%D9%8A%D8%A9|access-date=17 January 2022|website=alaraby.co.uk/|language=ar}}</ref>

On 10 November 2022, Bounou was named in Morocco's 26-man squad for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] in [[Qatar]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Morocco World Cup 2022 squad: Who's in and who's out?|url=https://www.goal.com/en-bh/lists/morocco-2022-world-cup-squad-hakimi-ziyech-mazraoui-qatar/blta36257fc4feeb66a |access-date=10 November 2022 |website=Goal.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=10 November 2022 |title=Moroccan coach unveils list of 26 Atlas Lions in 2022 World Cup |url=https://en.hespress.com/52697-moroccan-coach-unveils-list-of-26-atlas-lions-in-2022-world-cup.html |access-date=10 November 2022 |website=HESPRESS}}</ref> He made two saves during the round of 16 penalty shoot-out against [[Spain national football team|Spain]], leading to Morocco qualifying for the quarter-finals for the first time in their history,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lowe |first1=Sid |title=A beautiful day for Bono and Morocco in last-16 shootout win over Spain |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2022/dec/06/morocco-spain-world-cup-last-16-match-report |work=The Guardian |access-date=6 December 2022 |date=6 December 2022}}</ref> where they won 1–0 against [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]], becoming the first African team to reach the semi-finals.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ronald |first1=Issy |title=Morocco becomes first ever African team to reach World Cup semifinals with historic victory over Portugal |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2022/12/10/football/morocco-portugal-quarterfinals-world-cup-2022-spt-intl/index.html |access-date=27 December 2022 |publisher=CNN |date=10 December 2022}}</ref> He kept four clean sheets, the most out of any goalkeeper in the tournament.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mackenzie |first1=Alasdair |title=World Cup awards: who won the Golden Boot, Golden Glove and Young Player of the Tournament? |url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/world-cup/2022/world-cup-awards-who-won-the-golden-ball-golden-boot-golden-glove-and-young-player-of-the-tournament_sto9282131/story.shtml |access-date=27 December 2022 |publisher=Eurosport |date=18 December 2022}}</ref> He was the first African to reach three [[Shutout|clean sheets]] at a World Cup.<ref>{{cite news |title=Yassine Bounou Sets A New Stunning Record – 3 Clean Sheets |url=https://tembah.net/en/news?nid=23560 |access-date=27 December 2022 |publisher=Tembah |date=11 December 2022}}</ref>

On 28 December 2023, Bounou was amongst the 27 players selected by [[Walid Regragui]] to represent Morocco at the [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-12-28 |title=Regragui unveils 27 player list for Morocco's participation in CAN 2023 |url=https://en.hespress.com/77181-regragui-unveils-27-player-list-for-moroccos-participation-in-can-2023.html |access-date=2023-12-29 |website=HESPRESS English - Morocco News |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-12-28 |title=Regragui names 27 provisional players for AFCON |url=https://www.cafonline.com/caf-africa-cup-of-nations/news/regragui-names-27-provisional-players-for-afcon/ |access-date=2023-12-29 |website=CAF |language=en-GB}}</ref>

In October 2025, Bounou, with Morocco, broke the [[List of world association football records|world record for the longest winning streak in international football]], surpassing Spain’s previous mark of 15 consecutive victories. With a 1–0 win over [[Congo national football team|Congo]] in Rabat, Morocco extended their unbeaten run to 16 straight wins across all competitions, including World Cup qualifiers and friendlies. The streak, which began in June 2024, is ongoing, with Morocco continuing to extend their record as of October 2025.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Gleeson |first=Mark |date=14 October 2025 |title=Morocco beat Congo to surpass Spain's wins record |url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/morocco-beat-congo-surpass-spains-wins-record-2025-10-14/ |access-date=15 October 2025 |website=Reuters}}</ref>

On 11 December 2025, Bounou was called up to the Morocco squad for the [[2025 Africa Cup of Nations]], hosted on home soil.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cafonline.com/afcon2025/news/morocco-name-star-studded-afcon-squad-as-hakimi-makes-cut-but-diop-misses-out/|title=Morocco name star-studded AFCON squad as Hakimi makes cut but Diop misses out|publisher=[[Confederation of African Football]]|date=11 December 2025|access-date=12 December 2025}}</ref> Morocco eventually lost the [[2025 Africa Cup of Nations final|2025 AFCON final]] 1–0 against [[Senegal national football team|Senegal]] after extra time, but the result was overturned due to Senegal forfeiting the match after walking off to protest a referee decision.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2026-03-17 |title=Afcon 2025: Morocco declared the winners after CAF overturns final defeat to Senegal |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/ce949glzzglo |access-date=2026-03-18 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/live-blogs/senegal-vs-morocco-afcon-2025-final-score-result/DQtU75DqxAoW/ |title=Senegal beat Morocco thanks to Gueye strike in extraordinary AFCON 2025 final: Live updates and reaction |publisher=The New York Times |date=19 January 2026 }}</ref> Bounou was named Best Goalkeeper in the tournament.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.moroccoworldnews.com/2026/01/275558/yassine-bounou-crowned-best-goalkeeper-at-afcon-2025/ |title=Yassine Bounou Crowned Best Goalkeeper at AFCON 2025 |publisher=Morocco World News |date=19 January 2026 }}</ref>

==Personal life==
Bounou was born in Canada to Moroccan parents. Along with his [[Morocco national football team|national teammates]], Bounou donated his blood for the needy affected by the [[2023 Marrakesh-Safi earthquake]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-09-09 |title="أسود الأطلس" يتبرعون بالدم في أكادير |url=https://www.hespress.com/%D8%A3%D8%B3%D9%88%D8%AF-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D8%B7%D9%84%D8%B3-%D9%8A%D8%AA%D8%A8%D8%B1%D8%B9%D9%88%D9%86-%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AF%D9%85-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%A3%D9%83%D8%A7%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%B1-1229384.html |access-date=2023-09-09 |website=Hespress - هسبريس جريدة إلكترونية مغربية |language=ar}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title="أسود الأطلس" يتبرعون بالدم.. عالم الرياضة يتضامن مع المغرب بعد الزلزال المدمر |url=https://www.aljazeera.net/sport/2023/9/9/%d8%a3%d8%b3%d9%88%d8%af-%d8%a7%d9%84%d8%a3%d8%b7%d9%84%d8%b3-%d9%8a%d8%aa%d8%a8%d8%b1%d8%b9%d9%88%d9%86-%d8%a8%d8%a7%d9%84%d8%af%d9%85-%d8%b9%d8%a7%d9%84%d9%85 |access-date=2023-09-09 |website=www.aljazeera.net |language=ar}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=قطبي |first=ماجدة |date=2023-09-09 |title=زلزال الحوز.. الركراكي و"أسود الأطلس" يتبرعون بالدم |url=https://machahid24.com/sport/400897.html |access-date=2023-09-09 |website=مشاهد 24 |language=ar}}</ref> He is a Muslim.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Zidan |first=Karim |title=Faith, Fortune, Football |url=https://www.sportspolitika.news/p/faith-fortune-football |access-date=2025-10-29 |website=www.sportspolitika.news |language=en}}</ref>

